fession -- tPart III: A Man,His Theory, and His Network (1954–1994) -- t15.“My Hopes and Failures Are Within Myself” -- t16.“This Theory Hadn’t Made Much of a Stir, So Now,What Was I to Do?” -- t17. “I’d Better Make Sure I Learn a Little about Immunology” -- t18. “Finally,My Precious, I Have to Be Brilliant and Make Antibodies” -- t19.“Like a Log Coming Slowly to the Surface of a Lake” -- t20. “I Still Think That My Original Natural Selection Theory Was Better” -- t21. “Immunology Is for Me Becoming a Mostly Philosophical Subject” -- tEpilogue -- tABBREVIATIONS USED IN NOTES -- tNOTES -- tUNPUBLISHED SOURCES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis biography probes the unusual mind, the dramatic life, and the outstanding scientific work of Danish-born immunologist Niels Jerne (1911-1994). Jerne’s Nobel Prize-winning achievements in the field of immunology place him in the pantheon of great twentieth-century biomedical theorists, yet his life is perhaps even more interesting than his science. Science as Autobiography tells Jerne’s story, weaving together a narrative of his life experiences, emotional life, and extraordinarily creative scientific work.A legendary figure who preferred an afternoon of conversation in a Paris wine bar to work in the laboratory, Jerne was renowned for his unparalleled powers of concentration and analytical keenness as well as his dissonant personal life. The book explores Jerne the man and scientist, making the fascinating argument that his life experience and view of himself became a metaphorical resource for the construction of his theories. The book also probes the moral issues that surrounded Jerne’s choice to sacrifice his family in favor of scientific goals and the pursuit of excellence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (pu